# Test Plan — MCP Factory
**Document version:** 1.0  
**Date:** 2026-03-13  
**Project:** MCP Factory (Microsoft-Sponsored Capstone)  
**Team:** Evan King, Layalie & Caden, Thinh Nguyen  

---

## 1. Introduction

MCP Factory is a cloud-hosted web application that converts an existing binary (DLL, EXE, CMD, script, or installed program) into a deployable **Model Context Protocol (MCP)** server, allowing AI agents such as GitHub Copilot to invoke real Windows features through natural language.

The system is hosted on **Azure Container Apps** (East US, resource group `mcp-factory-rg`) and consists of two services:

| Service | Role |
|---------|------|
| UI Container App (`mcp-factory-ui`) | FastAPI-served Single-Page Application the end user interacts with |
| Pipeline Container App (`mcp-factory-pipeline`) | FastAPI REST API that orchestrates discovery, generation, execution, and chat |

The full product pipeline follows five sections defined by the project sponsor (Microsoft):

| Section | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| §2 | Specify Target — upload a binary or supply a server-side path |
| §3 | Display Invocables — list discovered callable features with confidence scores |
| §4 | Generate MCP Architecture — build and persist the MCP tool schema |
| §5 | Verify Output — interact with the generated MCP server via a chat interface |

This test plan covers **functional black-box testing** of requirements stated in the Microsoft requirements document and in the internal project specification ([docs/project_description.md](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/docs/project_description.md), [docs/sections-2-3.md](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/docs/sections-2-3.md), [docs/product-flow.md](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/docs/product-flow.md), [docs/architecture.md](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/docs/architecture.md)). The tester does **not** need access to source code; they need only a web browser and the ability to create small sample files.

**Scope of this document:** Functional correctness of the end-to-end pipeline as accessible through the browser UI and the REST API. Performance, security penetration, and FERPA compliance auditing are beyond this document's scope.

---

## 2. Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|------|-----------|
| **Binary** | A file executable on Windows 11/Win32, including DLLs, EXEs, scripts (Python, PowerShell, Bash, SQL, JavaScript, etc.), SOAP/WSDL service descriptions, OpenAPI specs, and COM type libraries. |
| **DLL** | *Dynamic-Link Library* — a Windows shared-library file (`.dll`) compiled to native machine code and exposing named exported functions. |
| **EXE** | *Executable* — a Windows application file (`.exe`) that can be launched as a process and may expose CLI argument-based invocations or GUI surfaces. |
| **Invocable** | A single callable surface discovered inside a binary: one exported DLL function, one CLI sub-command, one SQL stored procedure, one COM method, one GUI button action, etc. Each invocable has a `name`, `kind`, `confidence`, `description`, and `execution` block. |
| **Confidence Scoring** | A 6-factor quality analysis assigned to each invocable: [header_match](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/tests/test_fixtures.py#41-60), `doc_comment`, `signature_complete`, `parameter_count`, `return_type`, `non_forwarded`. Result is tiered as **HIGH** (≥ 6 factors), **MEDIUM** (≥ 4), or **LOW** (< 4). |
| **MCP** | *Model Context Protocol* — an open standard that lets an AI agent discover and call structured tools. An MCP server exposes a `tools/list` endpoint and a `tools/call` endpoint over JSON-RPC 2.0. |
| **MCP Schema** | A JSON document describing the available tools in OpenAI function-calling format ([type](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/tests/test_mcp_stdio.py#169-192), `function.name`, `function.description`, `function.parameters`). |
| **MCP Tool** | One entry in the MCP schema — corresponds to one selected invocable and carries enough metadata for an LLM to compose correct calls. |
| **Discovery Pipeline** | The server-side subsystem ([src/discovery/main.py](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/src/discovery/main.py) and supporting modules) that classifies, analyzes, and normalises a target binary into a list of invocables. |
| **GUI Bridge** | A Windows 11 VM (`mcpfactory-runner-vm`) running a private HTTP service on port 8090 that handles Windows-specific analysis and execution (pywinauto, COM, Registry) which cannot run in the Linux container. |
| **Job ID** | An 8-character hex identifier (UUID prefix) assigned to each analysis run. Used to poll status and retrieve results. |
| **Azure Blob Storage** | The cloud object store (`mcpfactorystore`) used to persist uploaded binaries (`uploads` container) and generated artifacts (`artifacts` container). |
| **Azure AI Search** | The vector search index (`mcpfactory-search`) used for semantic tool retrieval when more tools exist than the model's hard API limit (`OPENAI_MAX_TOOLS`). |
| **SSE** | *Server-Sent Events* — a unidirectional HTTP streaming protocol used by `/api/chat` to push token and tool-call events to the browser in real time. |
| **Artifact Hygiene** | The design principle that every output file must contain at least one valid invocable; files with zero discovered features generate *no* output (ADR-0005). |
| **FERPA** | *Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act* — US federal law governing the confidentiality of student education records. All Azure resources are scoped to the project team only. |
| **Agentic Loop** | The iterative model→tool→result cycle inside [api/chat.py](file:///Users/thinhnguyen/Code/mcp-factory/api/chat.py). The model calls tools, receives results, and iterates up to `MAX_TOOL_ROUNDS` until it produces a final text answer. |
| **`selected-invocables.json`** | The hand-off file produced by §3 that lists which invocables the user approved for MCP generation in §4. |

